'''Bottle-shock''' or '''Bottle-sickness''' is a  temporary condition of [[wine]] characterized by muted or disjointed fruit flavors. It often occurs immediately after [[bottling line|bottling]] or when wines (usually fragile wines) are given an additional dose of [[sulfur]] (in the form of [[sulfur dioxide]] or [[sulfite]] solution). After a few weeks, the condition usually disappears.<ref>[http://oneblockdiet.sunset.com/2009/02/bottle-shock-wh.html Sunset Magazine]</ref><ref>[http://www.winedefine.com/definition/bottle-sickness.html Winedefine.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626114752/http://www.winedefine.com/definition/bottle-sickness.html |date=June 26, 2011 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.winemakermag.com/stories/wizard/article/751-when-i-opened-my-blueberry-zinfandel-wine-i-was-struck-by-a-strong-acetone-type-smell-am-i-experiencing-bottle-sickness-or-tca WineMaker Magazine] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626090154/http://www.winemakermag.com/stories/wizard/article/751-when-i-opened-my-blueberry-zinfandel-wine-i-was-struck-by-a-strong-acetone-type-smell-am-i-experiencing-bottle-sickness-or-tca |date=June 26, 2011 }}</ref>

