'''Olga Constantinovna of Russia''' ({{OldStyleDate|3 September|1851|22 August}}{{spaced ndash}}18 June 1926) was [[Queen consort of the Hellenes]] as the wife of [[George I of Greece|King George I]]. She was briefly the [[regent]] of Greece in 1920. 

A member of the [[Romanov dynasty]], she was the daughter of [[Grand Duke Konstantin Nikolayevich of Russia|Grand Duke Constantine Nikolaievich]] and his wife, [[Princess Alexandra of Saxe-Altenburg]]. She spent her childhood in [[Saint Petersburg]], Poland and the [[Crimea]], and married King George I of Greece in 1867 at the age of sixteen. At first, she felt ill at ease in the [[Kingdom of Greece (Glücksburg)|Kingdom of Greece]], but she quickly became involved in social and charitable work. She founded hospitals and schools, but her attempt to promote a new, more accessible, Greek translation of the Gospels sparked riots by religious conservatives.

On the assassination of her husband in 1913, Olga returned to Russia. When the [[First World War]] broke out, she set up a [[military hospital]] in [[Pavlovsk Palace]], which belonged to her brother. She was trapped in the palace after the [[Russian Revolution]] of 1917, until the Danish embassy intervened, allowing her to escape to Switzerland. Olga could not return to Greece as her son, [[Constantine I of Greece|King Constantine I]], had been deposed.

In October 1920, she returned to Athens on the fatal illness of her grandson, [[Alexander of Greece|King Alexander]]. After his death, she was appointed regent until the restoration of Constantine I the following month. After the defeat of the Greeks in the [[Greco-Turkish War (1919–1922)|Greco-Turkish War of 1919–22]] the [[Greek royal family]] were again exiled and Olga spent the last years of her life in the United Kingdom, France and Italy.

==Family and early life==
Olga was born at [[Pavlovsk Palace]] near [[Saint Petersburg]] on {{OldStyleDate|3 September|1851|22 August}}. She was the second child and elder daughter of [[Grand Duke Konstantin Nikolayevich of Russia|Grand Duke Constantine Nikolaievich]] and his wife, [[Princess Alexandra of Saxe-Altenburg|Grand Duchess Alexandra]], a former princess of [[Saxe-Altenburg]]. Through her father, Olga was a granddaughter of Tsar [[Nicholas I of Russia|Nicholas I]], a niece of Tsar [[Alexander II of Russia|Alexander II]] and first cousin of Tsar [[Alexander III of Russia|Alexander III]].{{sfn|Montgomery-Massingberd|1977|pp=469–474}}

Her childhood was spent at her father's homes, including Pavlovsk Palace and estates in the [[Crimea]]. Her father was a younger brother of Alexander II,{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=26}} and her mother was considered one of the most intelligent and elegant women of the court.{{sfn|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|pp=69–70}} Olga was particularly close to her older brother, [[Grand Duke Nicholas Constantinovich of Russia|Nicholas]], and was one of the few members of the imperial family to keep in touch with him after he was banished to [[Tashkent]].{{sfn|King|Wilson|2006|pp=55, 109–110}}

As a child, Olga was described as a simple and chubby little girl with a broad face and big blue eyes.{{sfn|King|Wilson|2006|p=36}} Unlike her younger sister, [[Grand Duchess Vera Constantinovna of Russia|Vera]], she had a calm temperament, but she was also extremely shy. For example, when interrogated by her tutors during lessons, she burst into tears and ran from the classroom.{{sfn|King|Wilson|2006|pp=36–38}}

In 1862, Grand Duke Constantine Nikolaievich was appointed [[Namiestnik of the Kingdom of Poland|viceroy]] of [[Russian Poland]] by his brother and moved to [[Warsaw]] with his wife and children. The stay in Poland proved difficult for the Grand Duke, who was the victim of a nationalist assassination attempt the day after his arrival in the Polish capital.{{sfn|King|Wilson|2006|p=35}} Although Constantine embarked on a program of liberalization and re-instated Polish as an official language,{{sfn|Zeepvat|2007|p=70}} Polish nationalists agitating for reform were not appeased. Finally, an [[January Uprising|uprising in January 1863]] and the radicalization of the separatists pushed the Tsar to recall his brother in August.{{sfn|King|Wilson|2006|pp=34–36}} Olga's difficult experiences in Poland marked her profoundly.{{sfn|Christmas|1914|p=81}}

==Engagement and marriage==
[[File:1867. Портрет великой княжны Ольги Константиновны.jpg|thumb|left|Grand Duchess Olga Constantinovna, 1867]]
[[File:Queen Olga of the Hellenes.jpg|thumb|Queen Olga of Greece in a traditional Greek costume, circa 1870]]

The young King [[George I of Greece]] visited Russia in 1863 to thank Olga's uncle Tsar [[Alexander II of Russia|Alexander II]] for his support during George's election to the throne of Greece. Whilst there, George met the then twelve-year-old Olga for the first time.<ref name=times>''The Times'' (London), Monday 21 June 1926, p. 19.</ref>

George visited Russia again in 1867 to meet with his sister [[Maria Feodorovna (Dagmar of Denmark)|Dagmar]], who had married [[Alexander III of Russia|Tsarevitch Alexander]] (later Alexander III) the year before. He was determined to find a wife and the idea of an alliance with a Russian grand duchess, born into the [[Eastern Orthodox Church]], appealed to him.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=24–25}} Olga fell in love with George, but she was nevertheless anxious and distraught at the thought of leaving Russia.{{sfn|King|Wilson|2006|p=37}} Her father was initially reluctant to agree to their marriage, thinking that at the age of fifteen she was too young and, being close to his daughter, concerned by the distance between Greece and Russia. For her part, Grand Duchess Alexandra was much more enthusiastic than her husband and, when some members of the imperial family noted the extreme youth of her daughter, she replied that Olga would not always be as young.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=24–25}} Eventually, it was decided that Olga and George would marry when she had reached her sixteenth birthday. Meanwhile, she would continue her schoolwork until her wedding day.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=24–25}}

Olga and George married at the chapel of the [[Winter Palace]] in Saint Petersburg on {{OldStyleDate|27 October|1867|15 October}}. After five days of festivities, they spent a brief honeymoon at [[Ropsha]], south-west of Saint Petersburg. Over the following twenty years, they had eight children:
* [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine]] (2 August 1868&nbsp;– 11 January 1923), who was born ten months after the marriage of his parents; he married [[Princess Sophia of Prussia]] and succeeded his father as king;
* [[Prince George of Greece and Denmark|George]] (24 June 1869&nbsp;– 25 November 1957), High Commissioner of [[Crete]] from 1898 to 1906, married [[Princess Marie Bonaparte]];
* [[Grand Duchess Alexandra Georgievna of Russia|Alexandra]] (30 August 1870&nbsp;– 24 September 1891), married [[Grand Duke Paul Alexandrovich of Russia]]; their children included [[Grand Duke Dmitri Pavlovich of Russia]], one of the assassins of [[Grigori Rasputin]];
* [[Prince Nicholas of Greece and Denmark|Nicholas]] (22 January 1872&nbsp;– 8 February 1938), married [[Grand Duchess Elena Vladimirovna of Russia]];
* [[Princess Maria of Greece and Denmark|Marie]] (3 March 1876&nbsp;– 14 December 1940), married firstly [[Grand Duke George Mikhailovich of Russia (1863–1919)|Grand Duke George Mikhailovich of Russia]] and secondly [[Perikles Ioannidis]];
* Olga (7 April 1880&nbsp;– 2 November 1880);
* [[Prince Andrew of Greece and Denmark|Andrew]] (2 February 1882&nbsp;– 3 December 1944), he married [[Princess Alice of Battenberg]], their children included [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]; and
* [[Prince Christopher of Greece and Denmark|Christopher]] (10 August 1888&nbsp;– 21 January 1940), father of [[Prince Michael of Greece]].{{sfn|Montgomery-Massingberd|1977|pp=325–327}}

The Tsar told Olga "to love her new country twice more than her own",{{sfn|Carabott|1993|p=123}} but she was ill-prepared for her new life. Aware of her youth, she chose to retain the services of her governess to continue her education.{{sfnm|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|1p=69|Van der Kiste|1999|2p=25}} On arrival at [[Piraeus]], Olga wore blue and white, the national colors of Greece, to the delight of the crowd. On the way to the capital, popular unrest was such that Olga, who was not accustomed to such demonstrations, was close to tears. Unable to speak Greek, and with little time for rest, she attended official functions over several days. Overwhelmed, Olga was found sobbing under a staircase cuddling her teddy bear a few days after her arrival in the kingdom while she was expected for a formal event.{{sfnm|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|1p=69|Van der Kiste|1999|2p=26}} In less than a year, she learnt Greek and English.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=26}} On the advice of her mother, she took an interest in the archeology and history of Greece to gain public support.{{sfn|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|p=70}}

==Private life==
[[File:Silver jubilee of George I of Greece and Queen Olga.jpg|thumb|upright|Edition of ''[[Le Petit Journal (newspaper)|Le Petit Journal]]'' celebrating the silver wedding anniversary of King George I and Queen Olga, 1892]]

Throughout their marriage, George I and Olga were a close-knit couple,{{sfnm|Gelardi|2006|1p=181|Vickers|2000|2p=68}} and contrary to the prevailing custom spent much time with their children, who grew up in a warm family atmosphere.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=36}} With age, however, George I argued with his sons and Olga lamented the quarrels that divided the family periodically.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=53}} In private, Olga and George I conversed in German because it was the only language they both spoke at the time of their marriage. With their offspring, they spoke mainly English,{{sfn|Forster|1958|p=74}} although the children were required to speak Greek among themselves,{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=42}} and Prince Andrew refused to speak anything but Greek to his parents.{{sfnm|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|1p=73|Vickers|2000|2p=309}}

The life of the royal family was relatively quiet and withdrawn. The Athenian court was not as brilliant and sumptuous as that of Saint Petersburg,{{sfn|Michael of Greece|2004|p=27}} and days in the Greek capital were sometimes monotonous for members of the royal family.{{sfn|Bertin|1982|p=150}} In spring and winter, they divided time between the [[Hellenic Parliament|Royal Palace]] in Athens, and [[Tatoi Palace]] at the foot of Mount [[Parnitha]]. Summers were spent on vacation at [[Aix-les-Bains]] in France, visiting relatives in the Russian capital or at [[Fredensborg Palace|Fredensborg]] and [[Bernstorff Palace|Bernstorff]] in Denmark, and relaxing at [[Mon Repos, Corfu]].{{sfn|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|pp=70–73}}

Olga remained nostalgic for Russia. Her room was filled with icons from her homeland and, in the palace chapel, she sang Slavic hymns with her children. She often visited Russian ships that were docked at [[Piraeus]] and invited the Russian sailors to the royal palace.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=26, 39}} She was the only woman in history to bear the title of Admiral of the [[Imperial Russian Navy]], an honor given to her on marriage.{{sfn|King|Wilson|2006|p=37}} She was honored in the Greek navy by having [[Greek ironclad Vasilissa Olga|a ship named after her]].{{sfn|Driault|Lheritier|1926|pp=227, 319, 424, vol. III}}

==Social work==
[[File:Amalieion Orfanotrofeion Athinon.JPG|thumb|right|Amalieion orphanage, Athens]]
Olga was genuinely popular and was extensively involved in charity work.<ref name=times />{{sfn|Vickers|2000|p=67}} On arrival in Athens, her immediate [[patronage]]s included the Amalieion orphanage founded by the previous queen consort [[Amalia of Oldenburg]], and the [[Arsakeio]]n school for girls located on [[Panepistimiou Street|University Boulevard]]. With her personal support and the support of wealthy donors, she built asylums for the terminally ill and for the elderly disabled, and a [[sanatorium]] for patients with [[Tuberculosis|consumption]]. She founded a society to help the poor, a kindergarten for the children of the poor, and a soup kitchen in Piraeus that doubled as a cooking school for poor girls that was later expanded into a weaving school for girls and elderly women in financial difficulty.{{sfn|Christmas|1914|p=129}} She was patron of two military hospitals and endowed the [[List of hospitals in Greece|''Evangelismos'' (Annunciation) Hospital]], Greece's largest, in downtown [[Athens]].<ref name=times />{{sfnm|Christmas|1914|1p=131|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|2p=72}} She built the Russian Hospital in [[Piraeus]] in memory of her daughter, [[Grand Duchess Alexandra Georgievna of Russia|Alexandra]], who died in Moscow in 1891. Although aimed primarily at Russian sailors, the hospital was open to all seamen visiting Greece, with consultation fees set at the low rate of thirty [[Greek lepton|lepta]] and medicines being free.{{sfn|Christmas|1914|pp=130–131}} Olga also supported the establishment and funding of hospitals during the conflicts between Greece and its neighbors, including the [[Greco-Turkish War (1897)|Greco-Turkish War of 1897]] and the [[First Balkan War]] (1912–13).{{sfn|Christmas|1914|pp=265–266, 368}} For their work for the wounded, Olga and her daughter-in-law [[Sophia of Prussia|Crown Princess Sophia]] were awarded the [[Royal Red Cross]] by [[Queen Victoria]] of the United Kingdom in December 1897.{{sfn|Gelardi|2006|p=83}}

Before Olga's arrival in Greece, there were no separate prisons for women or the young, and she was instrumental in the establishment of a women's prison in the capital and, with the support of wealthy philanthropist [[George Averoff]], one for juvenile delinquents.{{sfn|Christmas|1914|p=130}}

Shortly after Greece's defeat in the Greco-Turkish War of 1897, shots were fired at Olga's husband and daughter by disgruntled Greeks in 1898. Despite the failed assassination, Olga insisted on continuing her engagements without a military guard.<ref name=times /> Her son [[Prince Nicholas of Greece and Denmark|Nicolas]] wrote in his memoirs that one day he spoke of the importance of public opinion to his mother, and she retorted, "I prefer to be governed by a well born lion rather than four hundred rats like me."<ref>"''Je préfère être gouvernée par un lion bien né que par quatre-cent rats de mon espèce''", quoted in {{harvnb|Nicholas of Greece|1926|p=51}}.</ref> Olga's interest in political and public opinion was limited. Although she favored Greece's [[Russian Party (Greece)|Russian party]],{{sfn|Driault|Lheritier|1926|pp=270, 477, vol. IV}} she had no political influence over her husband and did not seek political influence in the [[Greek parliament]].{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=41}}

==''Evangelika'' controversy==
[[File:Evangelika1901.jpg|thumb|left|''Evangelika'' riots in Athens, 1901]]
An [[Orthodox Christian]] from birth, Queen Olga became aware, during visits to wounded servicemen in the [[Greco-Turkish War (1897)]], that many were unable to read the [[Bible]].{{sfn|Carabott|1993|p=123}} The version used by the [[Church of Greece]] included the [[Septuagint]] version of the [[Old Testament]] and the original Greek-language version of the [[New Testament]]. Both were written in [[Koine Greek]] while her contemporaries used either [[Katharevousa]] or the so-called [[Demotic Greek|Demotic]] version of [[Modern Greek]]. Katharevousa was a formal language that contained archaized forms of modern words, was purged of "non-Greek" vocabulary from other European languages and [[Turkish language|Turkish]], and had a (simplified) archaic grammar. Modern or Demotic Greek was the version commonly spoken. Olga decided to have the Bible translated into a version that could be understood by most contemporary Greeks rather than only those educated in Koine Greek. Opponents of the translation, however, considered it "tantamount to a renunciation of Greece's 'sacred heritage'".{{sfn|Carabott|1993|p=125}}

In February 1901, the translation of the New Testament from Koine into Modern Greek that she had sponsored was published without the authorization of the Greek [[Holy Synod]]. The price was set at one [[drachma]], far below its actual cost, and the edition sold well. To mitigate opposition to the translation, both the old and new texts were included and the frontispiece specifically stated it was for "exclusive family use" rather than in church.{{sfn|Carabott|1993|p=124}}

At the same time, another translation was completed by [[Alexandros Pallis]], a major supporter of a literary movement supporting the use of Demotic in written language. Publication of the translation started in serial form in the newspaper ''[[Akropolis (newspaper)|Akropolis]]'' on 9 September 1901.{{sfn|Carabott|1993|p=126}} Purist theologians denounced this version as "a ridiculing of the nation's most valuable relics"<!--What is the actual source of this quote? The cited Watch Tower source indicates it is itself quoting this statement, but provides no source--> and [[Ecumenical Patriarch Joachim III of Constantinople]] denounced the translation.<ref>{{cite journal|date=15 November 2002|title=The Struggle for a Bible in Modern Greek|journal=The Watchtower|publisher=Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|url=http://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2002846|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref> A faction of the Greek press started accusing Pallis and his Demoticist supporters of blasphemy and treason.{{sfn|Carabott|1993|p=126}} Riots, peaking on 8 November, were started by students of the [[National and Kapodistrian University of Athens|University of Athens]], partly motivated by conservative professors.{{sfn|Carabott|1993|pp=128–130}} They demanded the [[excommunication]] of Pallis and anyone involved with the translations, including Olga and Procopios, the [[List of Archbishops of Athens|Metropolitan bishop of Athens]], who had supervised the translation at her personal request.{{sfn|Carabott|1993|pp=123, 129–130}}

Troops were called in to maintain order, and conflict between them and the rioters resulted in eight deaths and over sixty people wounded.{{sfn|Carabott|1993|pp=117, 131}} By December, the remaining copies of Olga's translation had been confiscated and their circulation prohibited. Anyone selling or reading the translations was threatened with excommunication.{{sfn|Carabott|1993|p=131}} The controversy was called ''Evangelika'',{{sfn|Carabott|1993|p=117}} i.e. "the Gospels question", after the word ''[[Gospel#Etymology|Evangelion]]'', Greek for "Gospel", and led to the resignation of the [[metropolitan bishop]], Procopius, and the fall of the government of [[Georgios Theotokis]].{{sfnm|1a1=Campbell|1a2=Sherrard|1y=1968|1p=198|2a1=Carabott|2y=1993|2p=131}}<ref>''The Times'' (London), Tuesday 26 November 1901, p. 9.</ref>

==Widowhood==
[[File:Funeral of George I of Greece.jpg|thumb|right|Funeral of George I, Athens, 1913]]
In 1913, the [[First Balkan War]] ended with the defeat of the [[Ottoman Empire]] by a coalition of Greek, [[Bulgaria]]n, [[Serbia]]n and [[Montenegro|Montenegrin]] forces. Greece was considerably enlarged at the expense of [[Turkey]], but divisions between the victorious powers in the [[Balkan League]] soon became apparent: Athens and [[Sofia]] vied for possession of [[Thessaloniki]] and its region.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=72}} To affirm Greek control of the main city of [[Macedonia (Greece)|Macedonia]], George I moved to the city soon after its liberation. Just as he did in Athens, he went about Thessaloniki without any meaningful protection force, and while out for an afternoon walk near the [[White Tower of Thessaloniki|White Tower]] on 18 March 1913, he was shot and killed by [[Alexandros Schinas]].{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=72–75}} Olga, who said her husband's death was "the will of God", arrived at Thessaloniki the next day. She and her family visited the scene of the assassination and accompanied the body of the king to Athens. He was buried in the royal cemetery at [[Tatoi Palace]].{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=76–77}}

George and Olga's eldest son, [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine]], became king and his wife, [[Sophia of Prussia]], became the new [[queen consort]]. Olga, as [[queen dowager]], was given the use of a wing in the royal palace but soon returned to her native Russia, to spend time with her younger brother, [[Grand Duke Constantine Constantinovich of Russia|Grand Duke Constantine Constantinovich]] and his family at his home, and Olga's birthplace, [[Pavlovsk Palace]].{{sfnm|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|1p=85|Michael of Greece|2004|2p=27}}

==World War I==
[[File:Pavlovsk Palace 1890-1900.jpg|thumb|left|[[Pavlovsk Palace]], near [[Saint Petersburg]]]]
In August 1914, Olga was in Russia at the outbreak of [[World War I]],{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=87}} in which the [[Allies of World War I|Allied or Entente Powers]] including Russia, Britain and France fought against the [[Central Powers]] including Germany, Austria-Hungary and the Ottoman Empire. She decided to stay in Saint Petersburg and establish a military hospital to support the Russian war effort.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=116}} Olga created a clinic at Pavlovsk Palace where she cared for wounded soldiers with her sister-in-law, [[Princess Elisabeth of Saxe-Altenburg (1865–1927)|Grand Duchess Elizabeth Mavrikievna]]. Other members of the imperial family, such as [[Princess Helen of Serbia|Princess Helen]] and Olga's granddaughter [[Grand Duchess Maria Pavlovna of Russia (1890–1958)|Grand Duchess Maria Pavlovna]] founded field hospitals at the front.{{sfnm|1a1=King|1a2=Wilson|1y=2006|1p=155|2a1=Michael of Greece|2y=2004|2p=78}} As the war continued, Olga became aware of the growing crisis in Russia, and attempted to warn [[Alexandra Feodorovna (Alix of Hesse)|Tsarina Alexandra]] in 1916 of the danger of revolution but the Russian empress refused to listen. A few weeks later, Olga attracted the fury of the Tsarina after signing a petition asking for a pardon for her grandson, [[Grand Duke Dmitri Pavlovich of Russia|Grand Duke Dmitri Pavlovich]], who had been exiled to the [[Persian Campaign|Persian front]] for his involvement in the assassination of Alexandra's favorite mystic, [[Grigori Rasputin]].{{sfnm|1a1=King|1a2=Wilson|1y=2006|1pp=163–164|2a1=Van der Kiste|2y=1998|2p=191}}
[[File:Queen Olga of Greece.jpg|thumb|upright|Portrait by [[Georgios Jakobides]], 1915]]
In contrast to Olga, her eldest son, King Constantine I of Greece, was determined to follow a policy of neutrality.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=89–90}} His maternal relations were Russian, and his wife was the sister of [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|Kaiser Wilhelm II]] of Germany. His policy brought him into conflict with [[Prime Minister of Greece|Prime Minister]] [[Eleftherios Venizelos]], who favored the Allies. Constantine was soon accused of being a Germanophile and the Athenian government was regarded with suspicion in London and Paris. In what became known as the [[National Schism]], Venizelos established a parallel government in Thessaloniki in opposition to Constantine.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=98–99}}

On the [[February Revolution|collapse of the Tsarist regime]] in February 1917, Olga's sister-in-law left Pavlovsk with her family, but Olga stayed, soon to be almost alone except for a single young domestic named Anna Egorova. (After the Revolution, Egorova entered the service of [[Prince Christopher of Greece and Denmark|Prince Christopher of Greece]] and became the governess of his son, [[Prince Michael of Greece and Denmark|Michael]].{{sfn|Michael of Greece|2004|p=78}}) Short of food, the two women were limited to eating a little dry bread soaked in poor quality oil. Their safety was far from assured, and a few days after the [[October Revolution]], [[Bolshevik]]s invaded and ransacked the palace. Olga was physically unharmed.{{sfn|King|Wilson|2006|pp=166, 186}} She accepted the need to leave Russia, but the Bolsheviks refused to let her go and diplomatic help from Greece was not forthcoming in the aftermath of the National Schism. In June, Constantine had been deposed and exiled to Switzerland. As the Allies did not wish to establish a Greek republic or see [[George II of Greece|Crown Prince George]] succeed his father, Constantine was replaced on the throne by his second son, [[Alexander of Greece|Alexander]], who was thought to be more favorable to the Allies and more malleable than his older brother.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=104–108}} Venizelos held power and the supporters of the deposed king were arrested or executed.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=112–115}}

==First exile==
After several months of appeals for help, the Danish legation in [[Russia]] issued Olga a passport, which she used to enter Germany on the eve of its defeat, eventually joining her eldest son and his family in Switzerland in early 1919.{{sfnm|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|1pp=89–90|Van der Kiste|1999|2p=116}} Other members of the Russian imperial family did not escape. Among those [[Shooting of the Romanov family|killed were the Tsar, Tsarina and their five children]]; Olga's brothers Grand Dukes [[Grand Duke Nicholas Constantinovich of Russia|Nicholas]] and [[Grand Duke Dimitri Constantinovich of Russia|Dmitri]] Constantinovich; three of her nephews Princes [[Prince John Constantinovich of Russia|John]], [[Prince Constantine Constantinovich of Russia|Constantine]] and [[Prince Igor Constantinovich of Russia|Igor]] Constantinovich; and the Tsarina's sister [[Princess Elisabeth of Hesse and by Rhine (1864–1918)|Grand Duchess Elizabeth Feodorovna]].{{sfnm|Montgomery-Massingberd|1977|1pp=470–476|Van der Kiste|1998|2pp=198–202}}

[[File:Laszlo - Queen Olga of Greece.jpg|thumb|upright|Queen Olga in old age by [[Philip de László]]]]
In Switzerland, Constantine I and his family found themselves isolated and without an income. The Greek government under Venizelos did not pay pensions to former rulers and prohibited any contact between the exiles and King Alexander. Already in fragile health, the former king became gradually more depressed.{{sfn|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|p=90}} The Russian Revolution and the National Schism deprived Olga of her immovable property and she was forced to live a much less lavish lifestyle than in the past.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=147}} She did, however, enjoy spending more time with her sons and grandchildren, from whom she had been long separated by the war.{{sfn|Vickers|2000|p=145}}

==Regency==
On 2 October 1920, King Alexander was bitten by a monkey during a walk through the gardens at Tatoi. The wound became infected and Alexander developed [[septicemia]]. On 19 October, he began to rave and called for his mother, but the Greek government refused to allow Queen Sophia to return to Greece.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=122–123}} Worried about her son, and knowing that his grandmother was the only other royal still in favor with the [[Venizelism|Venizelists]], Sophia asked Olga to go to Athens to care for Alexander. After several days of negotiations, the dowager queen obtained permission to return to Greece but, delayed by rough seas, she arrived twelve hours after her grandson's death on 25 October.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=123–124}} On 29 October, Alexander was buried at Tatoi; Olga was the only member of the royal family at the funeral.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=125}}

Still opposed to the return of Constantine I and Crown Prince George, the government of Eleftherios Venizelos offered the throne to Constantine's third son, [[Paul of Greece|Prince Paul]], who refused to ascend the throne before his father and older brother unless a referendum named him head of state.{{sfnm|Van der Kiste|1999|1pp=125–126|Vickers|2000|2p=148}} Only days after Alexander's death, however, Venizelos was defeated in [[Greek legislative election, 1920|a general election]]. On 17 November, Admiral [[Pavlos Kountouriotis]], regent since the death of Alexander, retired and the new prime minister, [[Dimitrios Rallis]], asked Olga to assume the regency. She served as regent for about a month until her son Constantine returned to the throne on 19 December after [[Greek referendum, 1920|a referendum in his favor]].{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=126}}

==Second exile and death==
[[File:Princess Aspacia, Prince Christopher and Dowager Queen of Greece.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Olga (center) with her son [[Prince Christopher of Greece and Denmark|Christopher]] and his first wife [[Nancy Stewart Worthington Leeds|Princess Anastasia]]]]
[[File:Vasilissa Olga CoA.jpg|thumb|upright|Olga's monogram used as an emblem on the World War II-era Greek destroyer [[Greek destroyer Vasilissa Olga (D15)|''Vasilissa Olga'']]]]
Constantine I returned to the throne 18 months into the [[Greco-Turkish War (1919–22)|Greco-Turkish War]], launched in May 1919. In September 1921, the Greek defeat at the [[battle of Sakarya]] marked the beginning of the Greek retreat from Turkey. Resentment among the allies for Constantine's policy during World War I prevented Athens from receiving outside support.{{sfnm|Bertin|1982|1p=230|Van der Kiste|1999|2pp=129–130}} [[Mustafa Kemal Atatürk]], the new leader of Turkey, regained [[Smyrna]] and [[Eastern Thrace]], annexed by Athens at the end of World War I.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|pp=134–137}}

Following [[11 September 1922 Revolution|a coup by disgruntled military officers]], Constantine I abdicated for a second time on 27 September 1922. With several other members of his family, including Queen Olga, he went into exile in Italy and his eldest son succeeded him for a few months on the throne as George II.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=137}} Within months, Constantine died in Italy. One of Olga's sons, Prince Andrew, was among those arrested by the new regime. Many defendants in the [[Trial of the Six|treason trials]] that followed the coup were shot, including senior politicians and generals.<ref>''The Times'' (London), Friday 1 December 1922, p. 12.</ref> Foreign diplomats assumed that Andrew was also in mortal danger, and [[George V of the United Kingdom]], [[Alfonso XIII of Spain]], the French president [[Raymond Poincaré]] and [[Pope Pius XI]] sent representatives to Athens to intercede on his behalf.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=140}} Andrew, though spared, was banished for life and his family (including the infant [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]], later Duke of Edinburgh and consort of [[Queen Elizabeth II]]) fled into exile in December 1922 aboard a British cruiser, [[HMS Calypso (D61)|HMS ''Calypso'']].{{sfnm|Van der Kiste|1999|1pp=140–141|Vickers|2000|2pp=170–171}}<ref>''The Times'' (London), Tuesday 5 December 1922, p. 12.</ref>

Unlike her children and grandchildren, Olga was given a pension by the government of the [[Second Hellenic Republic]], but she maintained so many of the faithful old servants who had fled Greece with her that she was usually left with no more than 20 [[Pound sterling|pounds sterling]] per month (worth about £{{Formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|20|1922|r=-2}}}} in {{inflation-year|UK}} prices{{Inflation-fn|UK}}) to meet her own expenses.{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=147}} She could, however, count on the support of her family, scattered throughout Western Europe. In the United Kingdom, she shared her time between [[Spencer House, London]], the residence of her youngest son, Prince Christopher; [[Regent's Park]], where her daughter, Grand Duchess Marie, rented a mansion; [[Sandringham House]], the home of her sister-in-law, [[Alexandra of Denmark|Queen Alexandra]]; and [[Windsor Castle]] and [[Buckingham Palace]], where her nephew, King George V, lent apartments.{{sfnm|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|1pp=92–93, 318|Van der Kiste|1999|2p=147}}

[[File:GrabKöniginOlga.jpg|thumb|upright|Olga's grave in Tatoi]]
Olga's final years were marked by ill health. Lameness restricted her to a wheelchair, and she stayed in Paris several times to undergo treatment for her eyes. Her poor eyesight caused George V much laughter when she mistook a statue of a naked [[Lady Godiva]] for one of [[Queen Victoria]].{{sfn|Van der Kiste|1999|p=140}} Increasingly dependent, Olga finally settled with her youngest son, Prince Christopher, shortly after the death of his first wife, [[Princess Anastasia of Greece and Denmark|Princess Anastasia]], in 1923. Olga died on 18 June 1926 either at Christopher's Villa Anastasia in [[Rome]],{{sfnm|Van der Kiste|1999|1p=147|Vickers|2000|2p=180}} or at [[Pau, Pyrénées-Atlantiques|Pau, France]].{{sfn|Montgomery-Massingberd|1977|p=325}}<!--Two in the morning on 19 June in the presence of her family at Villa Anastasia according to ''The Times'' (London), Monday 21 June 1926, p. 14.-->

Despite republicanism in Greece, Olga was still held in high esteem and the republican government in Athens offered to pay for her funeral<!--''The Times'' (London), Monday 21 June 1926, p. 14.--> and repatriate her remains to Greece. Nonetheless, her children declined the offer, preferring to bury her in Italy beside her son, Constantine I, whose body Greece had refused to accept.{{sfn|Vickers|2000|pp=180–181}} Her funeral was held on 22 June 1926 at the Orthodox Church in Rome<!--''The Times'' (London), Wednesday 23 June 1926, p. 15.--> and the next day she was laid to rest in the crypt of the Russian church in [[Florence]].{{sfnm|Van der Kiste|1999|1p=147|Vickers|2000|2pp=180–181}}<ref>''The Times'' (London), Friday 25 June 1926, p. 13.</ref> After the [[Greek monarchy referendum, 1935|restoration of the Greek monarchy in 1935]] she was re-interred at Tatoi on 17 November 1936.{{sfnm|Forster|1958|1p=198|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|2p=188}}

As much of her property had been confiscated by the [[Soviet Union]] and the Greek republican government, most of her estate comprised jewelry reported in ''[[The Times]]'' to be worth £100,000 ({{Inflation|UK-GDP|100000|1926|r=-5|fmt=eq|cursign=£}}{{Inflation-fn|UK-GDP}}). This was shared between her children and the children of Constantine I.<ref>''The Times'' (London), Tuesday 22 June 1926, p. 15.</ref> Traumatized by the events of the [[Russian Revolution]], Olga wished to sever all ties with the country in which her family had been massacred. Before dying, she made her grandson, King George II, swear to repatriate the ashes of her daughter Princess Alexandra, buried in the [[Peter and Paul Cathedral]] in Saint Petersburg. Her wish was fulfilled in 1940 after his restoration to the Greek throne.{{sfn|Mateos Sáinz de Medrano|2004|p=327}}

