'''Tsakonian''' (also '''Tsaconian''', '''Tzakonian''' or '''Tsakonic'''; Tsakonian: {{lang|tsd|τσακώνικα}}, {{lang|tsd|α τσακώνικα γρούσσα}}; Greek: {{lang|el|τσακώνικα}}) is a modern [[Hellenic languages|Hellenic language]] which is both highly divergent from other spoken [[varieties of Modern Greek]] and, from a [[philology|philological]] standpoint, is also [[Language family|linguistically classified]] separately from them. It is spoken in the [[Tsakonia|Tsakonian region]] of the [[Peloponnese]], [[Greece]]. Tsakonian descends from [[Doric Greek|Doric]], which was an Ancient Greek language on the Western branch of Hellenic languages, and it is its only living descendant<ref>[http://linguistlist.org/forms/langs/LLDescription.cfm?code=tsd Linguist List]</ref> (along with the debatable Maniot dialect of Modern Greek). Although Tsakonian is treated as a dialect of Modern Standard Greek,<ref>{{cite book|last=Browning|first=Robert|title=Medieval and modern Greek|year=1983|page=124|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Horrocks|first=Geoffrey|title=Greek: A history of the language and its speakers|page=382|edition=2nd|location=Oxford|publisher=Blackwell|year=2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Joseph|first1=Brian D.|last2=Terdanelis|first2=Georgios|chapter=Modern Greek|title=Variation typology: a typological handbook of European languages|editor-last=Roelcke|editor-first=Thorsten|pages=823–836|publisher=de Gruyter|location=Berlin|year=2003}} {{cite book|last=Joseph|first=Brian D.|chapter=Lexical diffusion and the regular transmission of language chang in its sociohistorical context|page=411|title=Handbook of historical sociolinguistics|editor1-first=Juan Manuel|editor1-last=Hernández-Campoy|editor2-first=Juan Camilo|editor2-last=Conde-Silvestre|location=Oxford|publisher=Blackwell|year=2012}}</ref> some compendia treat it as a separate language,<ref name="Moseley">{{cite book|last=Moseley|first=Christopher|title=Encyclopedia of the world's endangered languages|year=2007|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|at=s.v. "Tsakonian"}}</ref> since Modern Standard Greek descends from Ionic and Attic which are on the Eastern branch of the Hellenic languages, while Tsakonian (as a descendant of Doric) is the sole surviving member of the Western branch.
Tsakonian is critically endangered, with only a few hundred, mostly elderly, fluent speakers left.<ref name="Moseley"/> It is partially [[mutual intelligibility|mutually intelligible]] with [[Standard Modern Greek]].
==Etymology== It is named after its speakers, the [[Tsakonian people|Tsakonians]], which in turn may be derived from 'exo-[[Laconia]]ns' 'Outer Lakonians'.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}
==Geographic distribution== [[File:Pelopones ethnic.JPG|thumb|left|Old ethnic map of [[Peloponnese]]; Tsakonian-speaking areas in blue]]
Tsakonian is found today in a group of mountain towns and villages slightly inland from the [[Argolic Gulf]], although it was once spoken farther to the south and west as well as on the coasts of [[Laconia]] (ancient [[Sparta]]). There was formerly a Tsakonian colony on the [[Sea of Marmara]] (or Propontis; two villages near [[Gönen]], Vatika and Havoutsi), probably dating from the 18th century, whose members were resettled in Greece with the 1924 [[Population exchange between Greece and Turkey|population exchanges]].<ref name="Moseley"/> Propontis Tsakonian appears to have died out around 1970.
[[Geography of Greece|Geographical]] barriers to travel and communication kept the Tsakonians relatively isolated from the rest of Greece until the 19th century, although there was some trade between the coastal towns. The rise of mass education and improved travel beginning after the [[Greek War of Independence]] meant that fluent Tsakonian speakers were no longer as isolated from the rest of Greece. In addition, during the war, the Turkish army drove the Tsakonians east, and as a result, their de facto capital shifted from Prastos to [[Leonidio]], further making the people significantly less isolated.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mansfield|first=Peter|date=April 21, 2000|title=Letter from Tere-Sapunadzi|journal=TLS. Times Literary Supplement|doi=|pmid=}}</ref> There began a rapid decline from an estimated figure of some 200,000 fluent speakers to the present estimate of a speaker count between 200 and 1,000.<ref name="Moseley" />
Since the introduction of electricity to all villages in Tsakonia by the late 1950s, the Greek mass media can reach the most remote of areas and profoundly affect the speech of younger speakers. Efforts to revive the language by teaching it in local schools do not seem to have had much success. Standard Modern Greek is the official language of government, commerce and education, and it is possible that the continued modernization of Tsakonia will lead to the language's disappearance sometime this century.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}
The area where the language is found today in some villages Tsakonia slopes of Parnon in the southern province of Kynouria, including the towns of Leonidio and Tyros and villages of Melana, Agios Andreas, Vaskina, Prastos, Sitaina and [[Kastanitsa]].
===Official status=== Tsakonian has no official status. Prayers and liturgies of the [[Church of Greece|Greek Orthodox Church]] have been translated into Tsakonian, but the ancient [[Koine]] of the traditional church services is usually used as in other locations in Greece. Some teaching materials in Tsakonian for use in local schools have reportedly also been produced.<ref>P. Trudgill, D. Schreier (2006): Greece and Cyprus. In: U. Ammon (ed.), ''Sociolinguistics.'' Berlin: Mouton de Gruyter.</ref>
===Dialects=== Tsakonian is divided by scholars into three dialects, Northern Tsakonian, Southern Tsakonian and Propontis Tsakonian.
Another difference between Tsakonian and the common Demotic Greek dialect is its verb system – Tsakonian preserves different archaic forms, such as participial [[periphrasis]] for the present tense. Certain [[complement (linguistics)|complementisers]] and other adverbial features present in the standard Modern Greek dialect are absent from Tsakonian, with the exception of the Modern ''που'' ({{IPA|/pu/}}) relativiser, which takes the form ''πφη'' ({{IPA|/pʰi/}}) in Tsakonian (note: traditional Tsakonian orthography uses the [[digraph (orthography)|digraph]] ''πφ'' to represent [[aspirated consonant|aspirated]] {{IPA|/pʰ/}}). Noun morphology is broadly similar to Standard Modern Greek, although Tsakonian tends to drop the nominative, final ''-ς'' (''-s'') from masculine nouns, thus Tsakonian ''ο τσχίφτα'' for Standard ''o τρίφτης'' (''o tshífta''/''o tríftis'': "grater").
[[File:Leonidio-Tsakonian-sign.jpg|thumb|right|300px|(Tsakonian/Greek) "Our language is Tsakonian. Ask and they'll tell you./Groússa námou eíni ta Tsakónika. Rotíete na nioúm' alíoi./I glóssa mas eínai ta Tsakónika. Rotíste na sas poun.", bilingual (Tsakonian and Standard Greek) sign in the town of [[Leonidio]].]]
The Propontis dialect was much more heavily influenced by the modern [[Thrace|Thracian]] dialect, and although there were significant grammatical differences, its vocabulary was much closer to Standard Modern Greek. Compare the Northern and Southern word for water, ''ύο'' (''ýo'', derived from Ancient Greek {{lang|grc|ὕδωρ}}) to Propontic ''νερέ'' and Standard ''νερό'' (''neré'', ''neró'').
However, there has always been contact with [[Koine Greek]] speakers and the language was affected by the neighboring Greek dialects. Additionally, there are some lexical borrowings from [[Arvanitika]] and [[Turkish language|Turkish]]. The core vocabulary remains recognizably Doric, although experts disagree on the extent to which other true Doricisms can be found. There are only a few hundred, mainly elderly true native speakers living,<ref name="Moseley"/> although a great many more can speak the language less than fluently.
==Sounds==
===Vowels=== * '''A''' {{IPA|[a]}} can appear as a reflex of Doric {{IPA|[aː]}}, in contexts where Attic had ''η'' {{IPA|[ɛː]}} and Modern Greek has {{IPA|[i]}}: ''αμέρα'' {{IPA|[aˈmera]}} corresponding to Modern ''ημέρα'' {{IPA|[imera]}} "day", ''στρατιώτα'' {{IPA|[stratiˈota]}} corresponding to Modern ''στρατιώτης'' {{IPA|[stratiˈotis]}} "soldier". * '''Ε''' {{IPA|[e]}} {{IPA|[i]}} before vowels: e.g. ''Βασιλήα'' {{IPA|[vasiˈlia]}} instead of ''βασιλέα'' {{IPA|[vasiˈlea]}}. * '''O''' occasionally {{IPA|[o]}} > {{IPA|[u]}}: ''ουφις'' {{IPA|[ufis]}} < ''όφις'' {{IPA|[ˈofis]}} "snake", ''τθούμα'' {{IPA|[ˈtʰuma]}} < ''στόμα'' {{IPA|[ˈstoma]}} "mouth". Final {{IPA|[o]}} > {{IPA|[e]}} after coronals and front vowels: ''όνος'' {{IPA|[ˈonos]}} > ''όνε'' {{IPA|[ˈone]}}, ''χοίρος'' {{IPA|[ˈxyros]}} > ''χιούρε'' {{IPA|[ˈxjure]}}, ''γραφτός'' {{IPA|[ɣrafˈtos]}} > ''γραφτέ'' {{IPA|[ɣrafˈte]}}, ''χρέος'' {{IPA|[ˈxreos]}} > ''χρίε'' {{IPA|[ˈxrie]}}, but ''δρόμος'' {{IPA|[ˈðromos]}} > ''δρόμο'' {{IPA|[ˈðromo]}} * '''Υ''' Pronounced in Modern Greek {{IPA|[i]}}, this was {{IPA|[u]}} in Doric and {{IPA|[y]}} in Attic. The reflex of this phoneme in Tsakonian is {{IPA|[u]}}, and {{IPA|[ju]}} after coronals (suggesting an origin in {{IPA|[y]}}). ''σούκα'' {{IPA|[ˈsuka]}} corresponding to Modern ''σύκα'' {{IPA|[ˈsika]}} "figs", ''άρτουμα'' {{IPA|[ˈartuma]}} corresponding to ''άρτυμα'' {{IPA|[ˈartima]}} "bread"; ''λύκος'' {{IPA|[ˈlykos]}} > ''λιούκο'' {{IPA|[ˈljuko] [ˈʎuko]}} "wolf" * '''Ω''' {{IPA|[ɔː]}} in Ancient Greek, regularly goes to {{IPA|[u]}}: ''μουρήα'' {{IPA|[muˈria]}} (Ancient ''μωρέα'' {{IPA|[mɔːˈrea]}}, Modern ''μουριά'' {{IPA|[murˈja]}}), ''αού'' {{IPA|[au]}} < ''λαλών'' {{IPA|[laˈlɔːn]}} "speaking".
(Note: Tsakonian citation forms for verbs are participles, hence they are given as derived from the ancient participle in ''-ών''.)
===Consonants=== Tsakonian in some words preserves the pre-classical Greek [w]-sound, represented in some Ancient Greek texts by the [[digamma]] ''(ϝ)''. In Tsakonian, this sound has become a fricative {{IPA|[v]}}: ''βάννε'' {{IPA|[ˈvane]}} "sheep", corresponding to Ancient ''ϝαμνός'' {{IPA|[wamˈnos]}} (Attic ''ἀμνός'').
Tsakonian has extensive changes triggered by palatalisation: * {{IPA|[k]}} > {{IPA|[tɕ]}} : ''κύριος'' {{IPA|[ˈkyrios]}} > ''τζιούρη'' {{IPA|[ˈtɕuri]}}, occasionally {{IPA|[ts]}}: ''κεφάλι'' {{IPA|[keˈfali]}} > ''τσουφά'' {{IPA|[tsuˈfa]}} * {{IPA|[ɡ]}} > {{IPA|[dz]}} : ''αγγίζων'' {{IPA|[aŋˈɡizɔːn]}} > ''αντζίχου'' {{IPA|[anˈdzixu]}} * {{IPA|[p]}} > {{IPA|[c]}} : ''πηγάδι'' {{IPA|[piˈɣaði]}} > ''κηγάδι'' {{IPA|[ciˈɣaði]}} * {{IPA|[t]}} > {{IPA|[c]}} : ''τυρός'' {{IPA|[tyˈros]}} > ''κιουρέ'' {{IPA|[cuˈre]}}, occasionally {{IPA|[ts]}}: ''τίποτα'' {{IPA|[ˈtipota]}} > ''τσίπτα'' {{IPA|[ˈtsipta]}}, ''πίτα'' {{IPA|[ˈpita]}} > ''πίτσα'' {{IPA|[ˈpitsa]}} * {{IPA|[m]}} > {{IPA|[n]}} : ''Μιχάλης'' {{IPA|[miˈxalis]}} > ''Ν(ν)ιχάλη'' {{IPA|[niˈxali]}} * {{IPA|[n]}} > {{IPA|[ɲ]}} : ''ανοίγων'' {{IPA|[aˈniɣɔːn]}} > ''ανοίντου'' {{IPA|[aˈɲindu]}} * {{IPA|[l]}} > {{IPA|[ʎ]}} : ''ηλιάζων'' {{IPA|[iliˈazɔːn]}} > ''λιάζου'' {{IPA|[ˈʎazu]}} * {{IPA|[r]}} > {{IPA|[ʒ]}} : ''ρυάκι'' {{IPA|[ryˈaki]}} > ''ρζάτζι'' {{IPA|[ˈʒatɕi]}}. This sound appears to have been a [[Alveolar trill#Raised alveolar non-sonorant trill|fricative trill]] in the 19th century, and {{IPA|[ʒ]}} survived latterly only in women's usage in Southern Tsakonian. A similar change occurred with palatalised [rʲ] in [[Polish language|Polish]] and [[Czech language|Czech]], whereas [[Proto-Norse language#Consonants|in other languages]] it [[Rhotacism (sound change)#Linguistic shift|went in the reverse]].
In Southern Tsakonian, {{IPA|[l]}} is deleted before back and central vowels: ''λόγος'' {{IPA|[ˈloɣos]}} > Northern ''λόγo'' {{IPA|[ˈloɣo]}}, Southern ''όγo'' {{IPA|[ˈoɣo]}}; ''λούζων'' {{IPA|[ˈluzɔːn]}} > Northern ''λούκχου'' {{IPA|[ˈlukʰu]}}, Southern ''ούκχου'' {{IPA|[ˈukʰu]}};
Occasionally {{IPA|[θ]}} > {{IPA|[s]}}, which appears to reflect an earlier process in Laconian, but in others {{IPA|[θ]}} is retained though the word is absent in Standard Greek: ''θυγάτηρ'' {{IPA|[θyˈɣatir]}} > ''σάτη'' {{IPA|[ˈsati]}}, but Ancient ''θύων'' {{IPA|[ˈθiɔːn]}} (Modern ''σφάζω'' {{IPA|[ˈsfazo]}}) > ''θύου'' {{IPA|[ˈθiu]}}
Word-final {{IPA|[s]}} > {{IPA|[r]}}, which reflects an earlier process in Laconian; in Tsakonian, it is a liaison phoneme: ''τίνος'' {{IPA|[ˈtinos]}} > ''τσούνερ'' {{IPA|[ˈtsuner]}}
Word-initial {{IPA|[r]}} > {{IPA|[ʃ]}}: ''*ράφων'' {{IPA|[ˈrafɔːn]}} > ''σχάφου'' {{IPA|[ˈʃafu]}}
In the common verb ending ''-ζω'', {{IPA|[z]}} > {{IPA|[nd]}} : ''φωνάζων'' {{IPA|[foˈnazɔːn]}} > ''φωνιάντου'' {{IPA|[foˈɲandu]}}
Tsakonian avoids clusters, and reduces them to aspirated or prenasalised stops and affricates: * {{IPA|[ðr, θr, tr]}} > {{IPA|[tʃ]}}: ''δρύας, άνθρωπος, τράγος'' {{IPA|[ˈðryas, ˈanθropos, ˈtraɣos]}} > ''τσχούα, άτσχωπο, τσχάο'' {{IPA|[ˈtʃua, ˈatʃopo, ˈtʃao]}} * {{IPA|[sp, st, sθ, sk, sx]}} > {{IPA|[pʰ, tʰ, tʰ, kʰ, kʰ]}}: ''σπείρων, ιστός, επιάσθη, ασκός, ίσχων'' {{IPA|[ˈspirɔːn, isˈtos, epiˈasθi, asˈkos, ˈisxɔːn]}} > ''πφείρου, ιτθέ, εκιάτθε, ακχό, ίκχου'' {{IPA|[ˈpʰiru, iˈtʰe, eˈcatʰe, aˈkʰo, ˈikʰu]}} * {{IPA|[mf, nθ, ŋx]}} > {{IPA|[pʰ, tʰ, kʰ]}}: ''ομφαλός, γρονθία, ρύγχος'' {{IPA|[omfaˈlos, ɣronˈθia, ˈryŋxos]}} > ''απφαλέ, γροτθία, σχούκο'' {{IPA|[apʰaˈle, ɣroˈtʰia, ˈʃukʰo]}} * {{IPA|[ks]}} > {{IPA|[ts]}}: ''ξερός'' {{IPA|[kseˈros]}} > ''τσερέ'' {{IPA|[tseˈre]}} * {{IPA|[kt, xθ]}} > {{IPA|[tʰ]}}: ''δάκτυλο, δεχθώ'' {{IPA|[ˈðaktylo, ðexˈθɔː]}} > ''δάτθυλε, δετθού'' {{IPA|[ˈðatʰile, ðeˈtʰu]}} * {{IPA|[l]}} after consonants often goes to {{IPA|[r]}}: ''πλατύ, κλέφτης, γλώσσα, αχλάδες'' {{IPA|[plaˈty, ˈkleftis, ˈɣlɔːsa, aˈxlaðes]}} > ''πρακιού, κρέφτα, γρούσα, αχράε'' {{IPA|[praˈcu, ˈkrefta, ˈɣrusa, aˈxrae]}} * {{IPA|[rp, rt, rk, rð]}} > {{IPA|[mb, nd, ŋɡ, nd]}}: ''σκορπίος, άρτος, άρκα, πορδή'' {{IPA|[skorˈpios, ˈartos, ˈarka, porˈði]}} > ''κχομπίο, άντε, άγκα, πφούντα'' {{IPA|[kʰomˈbio, ˈande, ˈaŋɡa, ˈpʰunda]}}
{{IPA|[z, v]}} are added between vowels: ''μυία, κυανός'' {{IPA|[myˈia, kyaˈnos]}} > ''μούζα, κουβάνε'' {{IPA|[ˈmuza, kuˈvane]}}
{{IPA|[ɣ, ð]}} often drop out between vowels: ''πόδας, τράγος'' {{IPA|[ˈpoðas, ˈtraɣos]}} > ''πούα, τσχάο'' {{IPA|[ˈpua, ˈtʃao]}}
